china's transition to a market economy how far across the river siepr siepr stanford institute for economic policy research search the site enter your keywords main links home about siepr research at siepr education at siepr events at siepr people at siepr publications at siepr economics in the news support siepr contact us stay connected stay connected banner home publications profile display china's transition to a market economy how far across the river type scid working paper 69 author s yingyi qian jinglian wu published 08 1 00 region china download pdf abstract china's two decade reform since 1979 has evolved in two stages with the november 1993 decision marking a turning point the essence of this decision is to replace the planning system with a modern market system we examine the process of change in the mind set of the leadership and analyze its political economic and intellectual basis we then evaluate the progress made during the first five years 1994 98 to investigate the remaining challenges we choose to focus on what we regard as the core issue establishment of a free and competitive enterprise system by changing the government business relationship to an arm's length type three necessary tasks are i transforming state owned enterprises ii promoting private enterprises and iii establishing the rule of law in each we assess the current status and analyze the opportunities and difficulties for future development stanford university economics department stanford center for international development public policy program site map economic summit
